            Summary = "Tour the eight tabs of the sales order detail panel — Overview, Lines, Schedule, Shipments, Returns, Documents, Invoices, and Activity — and learn what each one shows and the warning badges that flag attention.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","detail","tabs"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## The Sales Order Detail Workspace\n\nClicking any row in the Sales Orders list opens the **detail panel** — a tabbed workspace that holds everything about that order in one place. The web address updates to point at the order, so you can bookmark or share the link. The panel header shows the order number and the customer name (click it to open the customer), with a close (X) button on the right.\n\nBelow the header is an **eight-tab bar**. Some tabs show a small count badge, and several show a yellow warning triangle when they need attention. Here is what each tab does.\n\n### 1. Overview\n\nThe default tab. It shows:\n- **Status / info grid** — the status chip plus Customer PO, linked Quote (clickable), Credit Terms, Requested Delivery date, and Confirmed date. Fields only appear when they have a value.\n- **Edit Details button (Draft only)** — opens an inline form to set Customer PO, Credit Terms, and Requested Delivery date. This is the only place to populate those header fields after a quote→order conversion. See *Editing a Draft Sales Order*.\n- **Fulfillment summary** — three at-a-glance stats: lines with jobs, lines shipped, and shipment count.\n- **Totals grid** — Subtotal, Tax (with the rate %), and the bold grand Total.\n- **Notes**, a scannable **barcode**, and **Created / Updated** timestamps.\n- **Action buttons** — Confirm (Draft only), Cancel Order (Draft or Confirmed), and Delete (Draft only). Destructive actions sit on the left, the primary Confirm on the right.\n\n### 2. Lines\n\nThe line-item table: line number, part number (clickable when linked), description, quantity, a combined **Shipped / Remaining** column (shipped is green when fully shipped, yellow when partial), unit price, and line total. On a **Draft** order this tab gains Add / Edit / Delete controls. When a line has jobs, an expander reveals each job's number, stage, assignee, priority, and due date. The tab shows a **count badge** of the number of lines and a **warning triangle** when one or more non-Draft lines have no job yet.\n\n### 3. Schedule\n\nA per-line milestone timeline (order → production → ship) with a visual timeline bar and milestone cards marked Done, Overdue, or Upcoming. A line whose milestones are slipping is flagged **At Risk**, and the tab shows a warning triangle when any line is at risk. The data loads the first time you open the tab.\n\n### 4. Shipments\n\nOne card per shipment, each linking to the shipment record and showing carrier, tracking number, shipped/delivered dates, shipping cost, and weight, plus nested tables of shipment lines and packages. A **count badge** shows the number of shipments; a **warning triangle** appears when the order is partially shipped (lines still have remaining quantity).\n\n### 5. Returns\n\nOne card per customer return (RMA) tied to this order — return number, status, reason, return date, and links to the original and rework jobs. A **warning triangle** appears when any return is still open (not Closed).\n\n### 6. Documents\n\nUpload, download, and delete files attached to the order — drawings, customer POs, packing instructions, PDFs, images, Office documents, and CAD files, up to 50 MB each. Each file shows a type icon, its size, and when it was uploaded. A **count badge** shows how many files are attached. See *Editing a Draft Sales Order* for how the rest of the order is changed.\n\n### 7. Invoices\n\nA rollup of every invoice generated from this order's shipments. Each card links to the invoice and shows amount, due date, payment status, and which shipments it covers. A summary at the bottom compares **Total Invoiced** against the **Order Total**. A **warning triangle** appears when there are shipped-but-not-yet-invoiced shipments — your cue to bill the customer.\n\n### 8. Activity\n\nThe chronological audit timeline for the order: confirmations, cancellations, line edits, header changes, and inline comments — every state change is recorded here.\n\n### Reading the warning badges\n\nThe tab warnings are a quick triage tool:\n- **Lines** triangle → a confirmed line has no production job yet.\n- **Schedule** triangle → a line is at risk of missing its dates.\n- **Shipments** triangle → the order is only partially shipped.\n- **Returns** triangle → an open RMA needs resolution.\n- **Invoices** triangle → a shipment has gone out but hasn't been invoiced.\n\nScan the tab bar first: the badges tell you where the order needs attention before you open a single tab.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Editing a Draft (Article) ────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Editing a Draft Sales Order",
            Slug = "sales-orders-editing-draft",
            Summary = "How to add, edit, and delete line items on a Draft order, edit the header fields (Customer PO, Credit Terms, Requested Delivery), and how a customer's price list auto-fills the line unit price.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","draft","editing"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Editing a Draft Sales Order\n\nA sales order is fully editable while it is in **Draft** status. Once you Confirm it, the line table and header become read-only (the order is now a commitment to the customer). This article covers everything you can change on a Draft from the detail panel.\n\n### Editing line items (Lines tab)\n\nOpen the order, go to the **Lines** tab. On a Draft, the tab shows an **Add Line** button and each row gains Edit and Delete icons.\n\n**Add a line:**\n1. Click **Add Line**. An inline form appears below the table.\n2. Use the **part picker** to search the Parts Catalog by part number or name and select a part. (A line can also be a lump-sum / ad-hoc line with no part — leave the picker empty and just fill the description.)\n3. The **Description** auto-fills from the part name; you can override it.\n4. Enter **Quantity** (fractional quantities up to four decimals are allowed) and **Unit Price**.\n5. Click **Save**. The line is appended and the totals recompute.\n\n**Edit a line:** Click the pencil icon on a row. The inline form opens pre-filled. Note that the **part link is fixed at add time** — editing lets you change the description, quantity, and unit price, but not the part itself. To change the part, delete the line and add a new one.\n\n**Delete a line:** Click the trash icon. A confirmation dialog appears. (A Draft order must keep at least one line.)\n\nEvery add / edit / delete returns the refreshed order, so the Subtotal, Tax, and Total update immediately.\n\n### Price-list auto-fill\n\nWhen you pick a catalog part on a line, the system looks up the **customer's price list** for that part. If an applicable price-list entry exists, the line's **Unit Price is filled in automatically** with the customer-specific price. If no price resolves, the field is left blank for you to enter manually. This keeps customer-negotiated pricing consistent without manual lookup — but you can always override the auto-filled price before saving.\n\n### Editing the header (Overview tab)\n\nThree order-header fields can be edited on a Draft from the **Overview** tab: **Customer PO**, **Credit Terms**, and **Requested Delivery Date**.\n\n1. On the Overview tab, click **Edit Details**.\n2. An inline form opens with the three fields.\n3. Update any of them and click **Save**.\n\nThis edit path exists specifically because an order created by converting a quote starts with these fields empty — and the Overview only displays header fields that have a value, so without Edit Details there would be no way to populate them post-conversion. Use it to record the customer's PO number, set payment terms, and lock in the delivery date before you confirm.\n\n### What you can't edit, and when\n\n- **Tax rate** is set in the create dialog. Header editing covers PO / terms / delivery only.\n- **Customer** is fixed at creation — it determines billing context and the applicable price list.\n- **After Confirm**, the Lines tab and the Edit Details button disappear. Lines, header, and totals are locked. If a confirmed order is wrong, cancel it (which preserves the audit trail) and create a corrected order rather than editing in place.\n\n### Drafts are auto-saved\n\nWhile you're filling out the **create** dialog (before the order is first saved), the form auto-saves to your browser so an accidental reload or logout doesn't lose your work — you'll be offered to recover it. This is separate from the order's Draft status: the create-dialog draft is local recovery; the order's Draft status is its server-side lifecycle state.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Tracking Fulfillment (Article) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
