            Slug = "sales-orders-tracking-fulfillment",
            Summary = "Use the fulfillment summary, per-line job drill-down, no-job warnings, the Schedule tab, and the Invoices rollup to see exactly where an order stands from production to billing.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","fulfillment","tracking"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Tracking Fulfillment from a Sales Order\n\nOnce an order is confirmed, the sales order becomes your single window into how that commitment is being fulfilled — from production jobs through shipments to invoicing. You don't have to hunt across the kanban board, shipments, and invoices separately; the SO detail panel rolls it all up.\n\n### The fulfillment summary (Overview tab)\n\nThe Overview tab shows a **Fulfillment** strip with three stats:\n- **Lines with jobs** — e.g. `3/4` means three of the four order lines have at least one production job created. A line without a job isn't yet in production.\n- **Lines shipped** — how many lines are fully shipped.\n- **Shipments** — the total count of shipments raised against the order.\n\nThis is your 5-second health check. `4/4 lines with jobs, 0/4 shipped` tells you the whole order is in production but nothing has gone out yet.\n\n### Per-line job drill-down (Lines tab)\n\nOn the **Lines** tab, any line that has jobs shows an expander chevron. Expand it to see each job linked to that line: **job number** (clickable to open the job), **title**, **stage** (e.g. In Production, QC/Review), **assignee**, **priority**, and **due date**. Archived jobs are flagged. This lets you trace a specific ordered part all the way to the shop-floor work producing it, without leaving the order.\n\n### No-job warnings\n\nA confirmed order line that has **no production job** is a fulfillment gap — nobody is making that part yet. The system surfaces this in two places:\n- The **Lines tab** shows a warning triangle in the tab bar, and the offending row is highlighted with an inline \"No job created\" warning.\n- These warnings only apply once the order is past Draft (a Draft order isn't expected to have jobs yet) and are suppressed on Cancelled orders.\n\nWhen you see a no-job warning, create the job (from the kanban board) so the line enters production.\n\n### The Schedule tab\n\nThe **Schedule** tab turns the order's lines into a milestone timeline — order date → production → ship — and flags any line as **At Risk** when its milestones are slipping past their target dates. The tab bar shows a warning triangle when at least one line is at risk. Use this to spot delivery problems early, before the requested delivery date arrives.\n\n### The Invoices rollup (Invoices tab)\n\nThe **Invoices** tab closes the loop on billing. It lists every invoice generated from the order's shipments, each showing amount, due date, payment status, and the shipments it covers. A summary compares **Total Invoiced** to the **Order Total** so you can see how much of the order has been billed.\n\nThe key signal here is the **uninvoiced-shipment warning**: when a shipment has gone out but no invoice covers it yet, the Invoices tab shows a warning triangle and a prompt. That's revenue shipped but not yet billed — your cue to raise the invoice.\n\n### Putting it together\n\nA typical fulfillment read on a confirmed order:\n1. **Overview** → fulfillment stats give the big picture.\n2. **Lines** → any no-job warnings? Drill into each line's jobs for stage/assignee.\n3. **Schedule** → any line at risk of missing its date?\n4. **Shipments** → what has actually gone out?\n5. **Invoices** → any uninvoiced shipments to bill?\n\nThe tab warning triangles let you triage all five of these from the tab bar at a glance.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Recurring Orders (Article) ───────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Recurring Order Templates",
            Slug = "sales-orders-recurring",
            Summary = "What recurring order templates are, how the nightly job auto-generates sales orders from them, the create flow, the interval/next-run model, and why templates are create-and-delete (no edit).",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders/recurring"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","sales","recurring","automation"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Recurring Order Templates\n\nSome customers order the same parts on a regular cadence — a standing monthly release, a weekly restock. Rather than re-keying the same order every time, you create a **recurring order template** once, and the system generates a fresh sales order from it automatically on schedule.\n\n### Where it lives\n\nRecurring templates live at **`/sales-orders/recurring`**. The page lists every template with its name, customer, interval, next run date, last generated date, line count, and an Active / Inactive chip. This area is available to Admin, Manager, and Office Manager roles (it is gated by the recurring-orders capability and may be hidden on installs that don't use it).\n\n### How auto-generation works\n\nA **nightly background job** checks every active template. When a template's **Next Generation Date** has arrived, the job:\n1. Creates a new **Draft sales order** for the template's customer, copying all the template lines (part, description, quantity, unit price).\n2. Records the run on the template (the **Last Generated** date updates).\n3. Advances the template's **Next Generation Date** forward by its **Interval (days)**.\n\nThe generated order lands as a normal Draft sales order in the Sales Orders list, where it follows the usual lifecycle — review, confirm, produce, ship, invoice. The template doesn't ship or confirm anything on its own; it only seeds the Draft so a person still reviews each release before committing it.\n\n### Creating a template\n\nClick **New Recurring** to open the dialog and fill in:\n- **Name** — a label for the template (e.g. \"Acme monthly bracket release\"). Required.\n- **Customer** — the customer the generated orders belong to. Required.\n- **Next Run Date** — when the first (or next) order should be generated. Defaults to one week out.\n- **Interval (days)** — how many days between generations (1–365). 30 ≈ monthly, 7 = weekly.\n- **Notes** — optional free-form notes carried for reference.\n- **Lines** — one or more part lines, each with a part, description, quantity, and unit price. At least one line is required; use **Add Line** for more and the trash icon to remove (you must keep at least one).\n\nSave, and the template appears in the list, ready for the nightly job to pick up on its Next Run Date.\n\n### Create-and-delete, not edit\n\nRecurring templates are intentionally **create-and-delete only — there is no edit**. The auto-generation job relies on the template's shape staying stable, so the workflow assumes template changes are rare. When a standing order needs to change (different quantity, new part, price update), **delete the old template and create a new one** with the corrected lines. Deleting a template stops future generations immediately; orders it already generated are unaffected — they live on as independent sales orders.\n\n### When to use a recurring template\n\n- A customer has a blanket / standing order with predictable releases.\n- You want each release to start as a reviewable Draft rather than auto-shipping.\n- The line set is stable enough that occasional delete-and-recreate is acceptable.\n\nIf the order changes every time, a recurring template adds little — just create each order directly instead.","sections":[]}"""
        });

