            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/sales-orders"]""",
            Tags = """["sales-orders","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Schedule Tab — At-Risk Milestones\n\nThe **Schedule** tab turns each order line into a milestone timeline running order date -> production -> ship. Each milestone reads as Done, Overdue, or Upcoming. A line is flagged **At Risk** when its target dates are slipping. When a line is at risk, its past milestones read as **Overdue** rather than merely Done.\n\n- When any line is at risk, the tab shows a yellow warning triangle.\n- The schedule loads the first time you open the tab, not when you first open the order.\n- At risk is worked out for you -- there's no switch to mark a line at risk by hand. Clear it by moving the underlying jobs forward.\n\n## Returns Tab — RMA Links\n\nThe **Returns** tab lists every customer return (RMA) tied to this order, one card each. Each card can carry up to two job links and flags a return that's still open.\n\n- **Original job** -- the job that produced the returned goods (shown when it's linked).\n- **Rework job** -- the job created to rework or replace the return (shown once rework starts).\n- Each link appears only when there's a job to point to; click either to open that job.\n- The tab shows a warning triangle when any return is still open (not yet Closed).\n\n## Partial Quantities & Prices\n\nLine **quantities and unit prices allow up to four decimal places** -- shops that work in units of measure need partial amounts (such as 2.5 kg or 0.75 hr). Every place you enter a line follows the same rules:\n\n- **Quantity** -- must be more than zero; the smallest allowed is 0.0001. Zero and negative are rejected.\n- **Unit price** -- can be 0 but not negative.\n- This holds in the new-order window, the line editor on the order, and the recurring-order window.\n- Whole numbers still read as whole numbers -- trailing zeros are trimmed.\n\n## Draft Auto-Save & Resume\n\nThe **new-order window** saves your work to the browser as you go, so an accidental reload or logout never loses it. When you reopen the window, you're offered to pick up where you left off.\n\n- This is **local recovery for the new-order window only** -- it's separate from an order's saved **Draft** status. The recovered work exists before the order is ever saved; Draft status is the first stage of an order that's already saved.\n- Recovery is offered on page reload and at your next login from the same browser.\n\n## Why the Order's Line List Is Read-Only After Draft\n\nA sales order is fully editable only while it's a **Draft**. The order shows Add / Edit / Delete line controls and the **Edit Details** header form **only** while it's a Draft.\n\n- Once the order is **Confirmed**, it's a commitment to the customer; the lines, header fields, and totals lock, and the editing controls disappear.\n- This is on purpose, not a limitation: editing a confirmed order in place would break the audit trail. To change a confirmed order, **cancel** it (which keeps the record as Cancelled) and create a corrected one.\n- The tax rate is never editable on the order itself -- it's set in the new-order window. The customer is fixed at creation because it sets who gets billed and which price list applies.","sections":[]}"""
